{{external links|date=November 2018}} {{Infobox philosopher |region = |era = |color = lightsteelblue |image = |image_size = |caption = |name = Ann Cudd |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |school_tradition = |main_interests = [[Feminist theory]], [[philosophy of social science]], [[social philosophy]], [[political philosophy]] |notable_ideas = |institutions = [[University of Kansas]], [[Occidental College]] |influences = |influenced = |signature = }} '''Ann E. Cudd''' is Provost and Senior Vice Chancellor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chancellor.pitt.edu/people/ann-cudd|title=Ann Cudd {{!}} Office of the Chancellor {{!}} University of Pittsburgh|website=www.chancellor.pitt.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> & Professor of Philosophy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philosophy.pitt.edu/person/ann-cudd|title=Ann Cudd {{!}} Philosophy {{!}} University of Pittsburgh|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|website=www.philosophy.pitt.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> at the [[University of Pittsburgh]]. From August 2015-August 2018, She was Dean of the College and Graduate School of Arts & Sciences at [[Boston University]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ann Cudd, Dean of the College of Arts & Sciences {{!}} BU Today {{!}} Boston University|url = http://www.bu.edu/today/2015/ann-cudd-dean-boston-university-college-of-arts-sciences/|website = BU Today|accessdate = 2015-10-08}}</ref> She was formerly Vice Provost and Dean of Undergraduate Studies as well as the University Distinguished Professor of Philosophy<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://philosophy.ku.edu/|title=Department of Philosophy|date=2013-10-29|work=Department of Philosophy|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref> at the [[University of Kansas]].<ref name=cv>{{cite web|last=Cudd |first=Ann |title=Curriculum Vitae |url=http://www.philosophy.ku.edu/people/cv/Cudd%20CV%202013.pdf |publisher=University of Kansas |accessdate=21 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331095720/http://www.philosophy.ku.edu/people/cv/Cudd%20CV%202013.pdf |archivedate=31 March 2014 }}</ref><ref name=vp/> She is also an affiliated faculty member with the Women, Gender, and Sexualities Studies Program<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wgss.ku.edu/|title=Department of Women, Gender, and Sexuality Studies|date=2014-08-27|work=Women, Gender, and Sexuality Studies|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en}}</ref>.<ref name=cv/> Cudd is one of the founders of [[analytical feminism]],<ref name=sepaf/> was a founding member of the [https://sites.google.com/site/analyticalfeminism/ Society for Analytical Feminism], and served as its president from 1995-1999.<ref name=cv/>
==Education and career== Cudd received a [[dual degree|dual]] baccalaureate in mathematics and philosophy from [[Swarthmore College]] in 1982 before going on to the [[University of Pittsburgh]] to receive a master's in philosophy, economics, and a doctorate in philosophy, in 1984, 1986, and 1988 respectively.<ref name=cv/> After receiving her doctorate, Cudd accepted a position at Assistant Professor at the [[University of Kansas]]. She left in 1991 for a similar position at [[Occidental College]], but returned to the University of Kansas in 1993. She was promoted to Associate Professor of Philosophy at the University of Kansas in 1994, full Professor of Philosophy in 2000, and received a secondary appointment as Director and full Professor of Gender and Women's Studies in 2001 (which she held until 2008, when she became an affiliated faculty member.)<ref name=cv/>
In 2008, Cudd became the Associate Dean for Humanities for the University of Kansas, and in 2012, Cudd was named Distinguished Professor, the highest academic honor the University of Kansas bestows on faculty members.<ref name=cv/><ref name=hh>{{cite web|title=KU names three new University Distinguished Professors|url=http://archive.news.ku.edu/2012/june/19/udp.shtml|publisher=University of Kansas|accessdate=25 March 2014}}</ref> In 2013, Cudd was named Vice Provost and Dean of Undergraduate Studies.<ref name=vp>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Gavin|title=Ann Cudd named vice provost, dean of undergraduate studies |url=http://www.news.ku.edu/2013/07/11/university-distinguished-professor-ann-cudd-named-vice-provost-dean-undergraduate-studies|publisher=University of Kansas|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref>
==Research areas and publications== Cudd's research has focused in several areas, namely feminist theory, the philosophy of social science, and social and political philosophy.<ref name=cv/> Cudd is one of the founders of [[analytical feminism]], a branch of feminism which seeks to apply the methods of [[analytical philosophy]] to feminist issues and topics.<ref name=sepaf>{{cite book|last=Garry|first=Ann|title=Analytical Feminism|date=24 April 2012|publisher=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/femapproach-analytic/}}</ref> She's authored two books and co-edited three more: ''Capitalism For and Against: A Feminist Debate'' (coauthored with Nancy Holmstrom in 2011, ''Analyzing Oppression'' in 2006, co-edited ''Philosophical Perspectives on Democracy in the 21st Century'' with [[Sally Scholz]] in 2014, co-edited ''Feminist Theory: A Philosophical Anthology'' in 2006, and co-edited ''Theorizing Backlash: Philosophical Reflections on the Resistance to Feminism'' in 2002.<ref name=cv/> She has also written dozens of articles in peer-reviewed journals, written several encyclopedia articles, and many book reviews.<ref name=cv/>
Much of Cudd's work analyzes power relationships through [[rational choice theory]].<ref name=sep1>{{cite book|last=Allen|first=Amy|title=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|date=Mar 9, 2011|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/feminist-power/}}</ref> Cudd's analysis of oppression argues that in an objective moral theory it is necessary to know whether or not harms experienced by individuals were indeed actual harms that the person shouldn't have suffered and are thus, in fact, oppressive. Cudd argues that the simple absence of good choices is not a form of coercion - for coercion to occur, objectively better choices must have been available to the subject.<ref name=jsop>{{cite journal|last=Willett|first=Cynthia|title=False Consciousness and Moral Objectivity in Kansas|journal=Journal of Speculative Philosophy: A Quarterly Journal of History, Criticism, and Imagination|year=2008|volume=22|issue=4|pages=290–299}}</ref>
