[[File:Christian August Brandis 1853.jpg|right|thumb|Christian August Brandis]] '''Christian August Brandis''' (February 13, 1790{{snd}}July 21, 1867) was a [[Germany|German]] [[philologist]] and historian of [[philosophy]].
==Biography== Brandis was born at [[Hildesheim]], and was the son of the physician [[Joachim Dietrich Brandis]]. His father moved to [[Copenhagen]] in 1810, where he became personal physician to [[Marie of Hesse-Kassel|Queen Marie]].
He was educated at [[Kiel University]]. In 1812 he graduated at [[University of Copenhagen|Copenhagen]], with a thesis ''Commentationes Eleaticae'' (a collection of fragments from [[Xenophanes]], [[Parmenides]] and [[Melissus of Samos|Melissus]]). For a time he studied at [[University of Göttingen|Göttingen]], and in 1815 presented as his [[inaugural dissertation]] at [[Berlin]] his essay ''Von dem Begriff der Geschichte der Philosophie''.<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Brandis, Christian August |volume=4|page=428}} This cites [[Friedrich Adolf Trendelenburg|Trendelenburg]], ''Zur Erinnerung an C. A. B.'' (Berlin, 1868).</ref>
In 1816 he refused an extraordinary professorship at [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]] in order to accompany [[Barthold Georg Niebuhr|BG Niebuhr]] to [[Italy]] as secretary to the [[Prussia]]n embassy. Subsequently, he assisted [[August Immanuel Bekker|Immanuel Bekker]] in the preparation of his edition of [[Aristotle]]. In 1821 he became professor of philosophy in the newly founded [[University of Bonn]], and in 1823 published his ''Aristotelius et Theophrasti Metaphysica''. With [[Philipp August Böckh|Böckh]] and Niebuhr he edited the ''Rheinisches Museum'', to which he contributed important articles on [[Socrates]] (1827, 1829). From 1836 to 1839 he was tutor to the young [[King Otho of Greece]].<ref name="EB1911"/> Brandis was elected a member of the [[American Antiquarian Society]] in 1839.<ref>[http://www.americanantiquarian.org/memberlistb American Antiquarian Society Members Directory]</ref>
His great work, the ''Handbuch der Geschichte der Griechisch-Römischen Philosophie'' (1835-1866; republished in a smaller and more systematic form, ''Geschichte der Entwicklungen der griechischen Philosophie und ihrer Nachwirkungen im römischen Reiche'', 1862-1866), is characterized by sound criticism.<ref name="EB1911"/>
Brandis died on July 21, 1867, in [[Bonn]], [[Germany]].
He was the father of the forestry academic and administrator [[Dietrich Brandis|Sir Dietrich Brandis]].
